Meanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Chesney","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and Irish (Antrim, Down): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac (an) tSasanaigh</b>, see   McChesney  .","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Chaney  , a cognate of 3 below.","French: topographic name for someone who lived by or in an oak wood, from Old French <i>chesnai</i> ‘oak grove’ (from <i>chesne</i> ‘oak’). Compare   Cheney   2."],"variants":[{"name":"McChesney","meanings":["Scottish (Galloway) and northern Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac (an) tSasanaigh</b> ‘son of the Saxon (i.e. the Englishman)’. The spelling seems to represent <i>Mac Shasanaigh</i>, to be pronounced originally as <i>McHasney</i>, rather than the English spelling <i>ch</i>."]},{"name":"Chestnut","meanings":["Scottish (Renfrewshire and Lanarkshire) and northern Irish: altered form of   Chesney  , shortened from   McChesney  . Its assimilation to the English word <i>chestnut</i> is due to folk etymology, the word itself being first recorded in 1519. The surname was probably taken to Ireland at the time of the 17th-century Plantation of Ulster.","English (Norfolk): probably a variant of <b>Chestney</b> (see   Chaney  ), altered by folk etymological association with the word <i>chestnut</i>."]},{"name":"Chesna","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Chesney  ."]}]},{"name":"Reynold","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Reinald</i>, <i>Reynaud</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>ragin</i> ‘advice, decision’ + <i>wald</i> ‘ruler’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them into England. In modern use, the given name sometimes represents a transferred use of the surname derived from the Norman personal name."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705184,"age":1,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":11,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Reynold de Chesney was born in 1095, in Addington, Surrey, England, his father, Philips Chesney Lord Addington, was 20 and his mother, Mrs Phillip de Chesney, was 21. He had at least 3 sons with Sybil fitz Alan."},"et":{"1105–":"1095–Surnud","1095–Male":"1095–Surnud","1282–1360":"1282–1360","1140–Male":"1140–Surnud","1300–1340":"1300–1340","1335–1400":"1335–1400","1075–1109":"1075–1109","1075–Female":"1075–Surnud","about 1140":"umbes 1140","1340":"1340","1075":"1075","1096":"1096","1140":"1140","1360":"1360","1282":"1282","1095":"1095","1106":"1106","1105":"1095","1335":"1335","1400":"1400","1300":"1300","Abt 1100":"umbes 1100","1109"